As we know, the Democratic party and the Republican party are two main parties of the United States, and each party has its own principle. The Democratic party advocates freedom and pays more attention to people’s welfare and multi-culture. The Republican party pursues conservative, and mainly focuses on building up an unrestricted market for business. So, as a president candidates of each party, they must follow the idea of their own party.

So, we could consider that:

What the political difference would be between two parties, from the perspective of the presidents and president candidates’ speech?

INTRODUCTION:

In this project, we are going to mainly demonstrate the statement if there exists any political difference between two parties, from the perspective of each party’ presidents and president candidates’ speeches. In other words, the inaugural speech each party’s president made would follow the principal of his or her own party or would be determined by current situation of country.

The analysis has following three parts:

  1. General Idea of structure of speech

  2. Sentimental analysis

  3. Topic Modeling & Analysis

Before analysis, some data processing work is necessary.

3.Generate list of sentences

sentence.list=NULL
for(i in 1:nrow(speech.list)){
  sentences=sent_detect(speech.list$fulltext[i],
                        endmarks = c("?", ".", "!", "|",";"))
  if(length(sentences)>0){
    emotions=get_nrc_sentiment(sentences)
    word.count=word_count(sentences)
    # colnames(emotions)=paste0("emo.", colnames(emotions))
    # in case the word counts are zeros?
    emotions=diag(1/(word.count+0.01))%*%as.matrix(emotions)
    sentence.list=rbind(sentence.list, 
                        cbind(speech.list[i,-ncol(speech.list)],
                              sentences=as.character(sentences), 
                              word.count,
                              emotions,
                              sent.id=1:length(sentences)
                              )
    )
  }
}


#Some non-sentences exist in raw data due to erroneous extra end-of-sentence marks. 
sentence.list=
  sentence.list%>%
  filter(!is.na(word.count))

Compared with the nomination speeches, the inaugural Speeches are more interesting, since the length of speech is approximately same, but the sentence is much shorter.

Next, we find out the mean value of all different kinds of emotion for each party’s president, which calculated by the emotion data of the democratic and republican presidents’ inaugural speech. The result shows that the strength of emotion of the Republican president is stronger than of the democratic president, especially the value of anticipation. In other words, the higher value of anger, anticipation, and trust indicates that republican presidents are more aggressive when they make inaugural speech. It also indicates that the Democratic presidents is ambition about their future development as a president of the United Sates.

After an overview of each party’s mean value of emotion rate, we could come up with clustering plot to find out if each party’s presidents have some similarity.

According to the cluster plot of emotion, we could find out that, basically, democratic presidents have same speech style in emotion. For example, the red clustering area has more Democratic president. Republican clusters are more dispersive, like the green area, which has Trump Donald and Hoover Herbert, and dark yellow area has Reagan Ronald and Bush W. George.

In conclusion, democratic presidents would usually stick with their consistent speech style, which could be verified by emotion cluster plot. However, Republican president would like to come up with several distinctive styles, but rarely same as democratic president’s style. In this way, it indicates that the democratic presidents’ speech has its own “democratic style”. For Republican presidents, their style will be more diversified, and president’s speech would follow one of the them. However, The sentimental analysis might not give a obvious difference between two parties, and the following part, topic modeling, will give us a better idea about what’s the topic difference between each party’s president. It will further show that if there exist the political difference between each party’s presidents.

c.Topic Modeling&Analysis

First of all, we need make a corpus of senence sinipets to run LDA and form a topic list

#For topic modeling, we prepare a corpus of sentence snipets as follows. For each speech, we start with sentences and prepare a snipet with a given sentence with the flanking sentences. 

corpus.list=sentence.list[2:(nrow(sentence.list)-1), ]
sentence.pre=sentence.list$sentences[1:(nrow(sentence.list)-2)]
sentence.post=sentence.list$sentences[3:(nrow(sentence.list)-1)]
corpus.list$snipets=paste(sentence.pre, corpus.list$sentences, sentence.post, sep=" ")
rm.rows=(1:nrow(corpus.list))[corpus.list$sent.id==1]
rm.rows=c(rm.rows, rm.rows-1)
corpus.list=corpus.list[-rm.rows, ]
# Text basic processing
docs <- Corpus(VectorSource(corpus.list$snipets))
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))

#Adapted from <https://eight2late.wordpress.com/2015/09/29/a-gentle-introduction-to-topic-modeling-using-r/>.
#remove potentially problematic symbols
docs <-tm_map(docs,content_transformer(tolower))
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))

#remove punctuation
docs <- tm_map(docs, removePunctuation)
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))

#Strip digits
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers)
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))

#remove stopwords
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))

#remove whitespace
docs <- tm_map(docs, stripWhitespace)
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))

#Stem document
docs <- tm_map(docs,stemDocument)
#writeLines(as.character(docs[[sample(1:nrow(corpus.list), 1)]]))
#Run LDA   
#Find the number of topics used in each speech
#Set parameters for Gibbs sampling
burnin <- 4000
iter <- 2000
thin <- 500
seed <-list(2003,5,63,100001,765)
nstart <- 5
best <- TRUE

#Number of topics
k <- 15

#Run LDA using Gibbs sampling
ldaOut <-LDA(dtm, k, method="Gibbs", control=list(nstart=nstart, 
                                                 seed = seed, best=best,
                                                 burnin = burnin, iter = iter, 
                                                 thin=thin))


#write out results
#docs to topics
ldaOut.topics <- as.matrix(topics(ldaOut))
table(c(1:k, ldaOut.topics))
write.csv(ldaOut.topics,file=paste("D:/Spring 2018/GR5243 APPLIED DATA SCIENCE/Project 1/LDAGibbs",k,"DocsToTopics.csv"))


#top 6 terms in each topic
ldaOut.terms <- as.matrix(terms(ldaOut,20))
write.csv(ldaOut.terms,file=paste("D:/Spring 2018/GR5243 APPLIED DATA SCIENCE/Project 1/LDAGibbs",k,"TopicsToTerms.csv"))


#probabilities associated with each topic assignment
topicProbabilities <- as.data.frame(ldaOut@gamma)
write.csv(topicProbabilities,file=paste("D:/Spring 2018/GR5243 APPLIED DATA SCIENCE/Project 1/LDAGibbs",k,"TopicProbabilities.csv"))
terms.beta=ldaOut@beta
terms.beta=scale(terms.beta)
topics.terms=NULL
for(i in 1:k){
  topics.terms=rbind(topics.terms, ldaOut@terms[order(terms.beta[i,], decreasing = TRUE)[1:7]])
}

After that, we could find out that what the most popular term of each topic.

#topic overview
tidy.lda <- tidy(ldaOut)
top.terms <- tidy.lda %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  top_n(6, beta) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -beta)

top.terms %>%
  mutate(term = reorder(term, beta)) %>%
  group_by(topic, term) %>%    
  arrange(desc(beta)) %>%  
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(term = factor(paste(term, topic, sep = "__"), 
                       levels = rev(paste(term, topic, sep = "__")))) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(term, beta, fill = as.factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = function(x) gsub("__.+$", "", x)) +
  labs(title = "Top 15 terms in each LDA topic",
       x = NULL, y = expression(beta)) +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, ncol = 5, scales = "free")

So, we use LDA to make topic modeling, and select 6 highest frequency words of 15 topics, and it helps us to figure out what’s each topic related to, and we could get an overview of the popular topics of inaugural speeches. According to our term list, we could conclude following list for 15 topics: “Economy”, “Responsibility”, “Defense”, “Belief”, “Business”, “Patriotism”, “Election”, “Government”, “Reform”, “American”, “Employment”, “Freedom”, “World”, “Legislation”, and “War”.

We make these 15 topics in topic hash, and to do further analysis

topics.hash=c("Economy", "Resonsibility", "Defense", "Belief","Business", "Patriotism", "Election", "Government", "Reform", "American", "Employment", "Freedom", "World",  "Legislation", "War")

corpus.list$ldatopic=as.vector(ldaOut.topics)

#WORDcLOUD 
folder.path="C:/Users/zhuqi/Documents/GitHub/ADS_Teaching/Tutorials/wk2-TextMining/data/fulltext/"

ff.all<-VCorpus(DirSource(folder.path))

ff.all<-tm_map(ff.all, stripWhitespace)
ff.all<-tm_map(ff.all, content_transformer(tolower))
ff.all<-tm_map(ff.all, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
ff.all<-tm_map(ff.all, removeWords, character(0))
ff.all<-tm_map(ff.all, removePunctuation)

tdm.all<-TermDocumentMatrix(ff.all)
tdm.tidy=tidy(tdm.all)
tdm.overall=summarise(group_by(tdm.tidy, term), sum(count))


dtm1 <- DocumentTermMatrix(ff.all,
                          control = list(weighting = function(x)
                                             weightTfIdf(x, 
                                                         normalize =FALSE),
                                         stopwords = TRUE))
ff.dtm=tidy(dtm1)

split_filename<-function(vec){
  x<-strsplit(vec,split = "")[[1]]
  matches<-gregexpr(pattern ="[A-Z][a-zA-Z]+-" , text = vec)
  p.name<-regmatches(vec, matches)
  p.name<-strsplit(p.name[[1]],split = "")[[1]]
  p.name<-paste(p.name[-length(p.name)],collapse = "")
  term<-x[length(x)-4]

  return(c(as.character(x[1]),as.character(p.name),as.character(term)))
}
library(plyr)

ff.dtm[,4:6]<-laply(ff.dtm$document,split_filename)
colnames(ff.dtm)[4:6]<-c("type","president","Term")

list<-c("BarackObama", "FranklinDRoosevelt","DonaldJTrump", "GeorgeWBush", "JohnFKennedy") 
plot.wcloud<-function(i = 1,t = 1){
text_inaug<-ff.dtm%>%
  filter(president==list[i],type=="i",Term==t)

wordcloud(text_inaug$term, text_inaug$count/sum(text_inaug$count),
          scale=c(4,0.3),
          max.words=100,
          min.freq=1,
          random.order=FALSE,
          rot.per=0.1,
          use.r.layout=T,
          random.color=FALSE,
          colors=brewer.pal(9,"Blues"),main="inagu")
text(0.5,-0.1,"\"Inaug\"",col="black",cex=1.2)

}

Looking at the cloud plot of Barack Obama, the word “icy” has the highest frequncy, and second noticable term is “storm”. Other remarkable words also have “crisis”, “ambitions”, and “doers”, etc. It could imply that Obama is trying to descript the severity of financial crsis at that time, which he used the metaphor of “winter” and “storm”. For Franklin D. Roosevelt, the keys words, “helped”, “emergency”, and “changers”, could show that he is trying to devote himself to change current situation of the United States. Both elected presidents were facing an unfavorable economic situation of country at that time, but the language between their speeches is still quite different. The keywords of Obama’s speech is more likely to depict how bad the situation is now, but the keywords of Roosevelt’s is trying to offer help.

Howver, according to the topic modeling analysis, we could demonstrate the inaugural speeches they made is based on current situation of country, and each party’s presidents have only little similarities in their topic selected. In this way, we could classfied that when each president deals with the problem of country, they are not belonging to any parties. Instead, they are representing the will of people.
